WEBVTT

1
00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:08.400
Hi, I'm Deepesh, and I'll be your instructor in this competitor sales analysis case study.

2
00:00:08.400 --> 00:00:12.960
A case study allows you to apply your skills and combine the skills you have

3
00:00:12.960 --> 00:00:18.200
learned in the previous courses by practicing them in a real-world business scenario.

4
00:00:18.200 --> 00:00:25.240
For this case study, no new concepts will be introduced which are already there in the below prerequisite courses.

5
00:00:25.240 --> 00:00:33.840
When we work on a BI solution, identifying and solving the end user's needs is the best place to start.

6
00:00:33.840 --> 00:00:37.160
Access to the data that lives in different systems and locations.

7
00:00:37.160 --> 00:00:38.640
Cleaning the data.

8
00:00:38.640 --> 00:00:44.360
Combine the data from all the disparate data sources to produce the needed reports.

9
00:00:44.360 --> 00:00:46.960
Exploring and analyzing the data.

10
00:00:46.960 --> 00:00:56.640
As we usually say, a picture is worth 1000 words; so visualizing it, and share the results with the other end users.

11
00:00:56.640 --> 00:01:02.040
Sharing of the reports and dashboards is outside the scope of this case study.

12
00:01:02.040 --> 00:01:06.120
The core goal of this case study is to build a report using a fictional

13
00:01:06.120 --> 00:01:12.440
Sales and Market share dataset for a manufacturing company called Sintec.

14
00:01:12.440 --> 00:01:17.240
Sintec is looking for a solution to focus not only on the company's performance

15
00:01:17.240 --> 00:01:22.760
internally on how well their products sell but also analyze other top

16
00:01:22.760 --> 00:01:29.240
competitors' sales and how well they are performing against the other competitors' products.

17
00:01:29.240 --> 00:01:36.720
In this case study, we'll create a snowflake-based schema and work with fact and dimension tables.

18
00:01:36.720 --> 00:01:43.800
The data is spread across six countries in one folder, and USA's data is in a separate folder.

19
00:01:43.800 --> 00:01:47.080
So we are going to work with one fact table that will be

20
00:01:47.080 --> 00:01:52.680
created through the transformations step by combining multiple files.

21
00:01:52.680 --> 00:01:59.920
The final fact table stores all the transactional data by date, product, and zip code.

22
00:01:59.920 --> 00:02:04.520
In addition, we'll be working with multiple dimension tables.

23
00:02:04.520 --> 00:02:12.360
Dimension tables are often highly de-normalized because these structures are not built to manage transactions.

24
00:02:12.360 --> 00:02:19.360
Instead, they are built to enable users to analyze data as easily as possible.

25
00:02:19.360 --> 00:02:25.320
We have four dimension tables: Geography having city, state, and zip details.

26
00:02:25.320 --> 00:02:30.880
Product table comprising of products data along with their price.

27
00:02:30.880 --> 00:02:38.200
The manufacturer table contains the manufacturer's information, and the Date table.

28
00:02:38.200 --> 00:02:45.000
The Date table will be created using DAX calculations during the case study.

29
00:02:45.000 --> 00:02:48.400
This is what our final data model will look like.

30
00:02:48.400 --> 00:02:57.440
It follows a snowflake schema where we'll have one dimension table that isn't directly connected to the fact table.

31
00:02:57.440 --> 00:03:02.880
Let's dive deeper into the case study and start our journey.

